output:
Use `cc.audioEngine.playMusic` to play background music:

```typescript
// Play background music looping
cc.audioEngine.playMusic('res/audio/bgm_main.mp3', true);

// Play once (no loop)
cc.audioEngine.playMusic('res/audio/bgm_victory.mp3', false);

// Set volume (0.0 to 1.0)
cc.audioEngine.setMusicVolume(0.7);
```

`playMusic(url, loop)` plays a single background track. The `loop` parameter controls whether it repeats. Only one music track can play at a time — calling `playMusic` again replaces the current track. Use `setMusicVolume` to control volume on a 0.0–1.0 scale.

`playEffect` returns a numeric audio ID that you can use to control the specific effect instance:

```typescript
// Play a one-shot effect
cc.audioEngine.playEffect('res/audio/sfx_coin.mp3');

// Play a looping effect and store the ID
const engineId = cc.audioEngine.playEffect('res/audio/sfx_engine.mp3', true);

// Pause the specific effect
cc.audioEngine.pauseEffect(engineId);

// Resume it
cc.audioEngine.resumeEffect(engineId);

// Stop it
cc.audioEngine.stopEffect(engineId);
```

`playEffect` returns `number | null`. The audio ID is unique to that specific playback instance. You can have multiple effects playing simultaneously, each controlled independently via their IDs.

Use `pauseMusic` and `resumeMusic` on `cc.audioEngine`:

```typescript
// Start music
cc.audioEngine.playMusic('res/audio/bgm_main.mp3', true);

// Pause when game is paused
cc.audioEngine.pauseMusic();

// Resume when game continues
cc.audioEngine.resumeMusic();

// Check if music is currently playing
const isPlaying: boolean = cc.audioEngine.isMusicPlaying();
if (isPlaying) {
    cc.audioEngine.pauseMusic();
}

// Restart from the beginning
cc.audioEngine.rewindMusic();
```

`pauseMusic` freezes playback at the current position. `resumeMusic` continues from where it was paused. `rewindMusic` restarts the track from the beginning without stopping it. `isMusicPlaying` returns `true` if music is actively playing (not paused or stopped).

Use `preloadMusic` and `preloadEffect` to load audio into memory before playing:

```typescript
// Preload during scene initialization
cc.audioEngine.preloadMusic('res/audio/bgm_main.mp3');
cc.audioEngine.preloadEffect('res/audio/sfx_hit.mp3');
cc.audioEngine.preloadEffect('res/audio/sfx_coin.mp3');
cc.audioEngine.preloadEffect('res/audio/sfx_jump.mp3');

// Later, play instantly without loading delay
cc.audioEngine.playMusic('res/audio/bgm_main.mp3', true);
cc.audioEngine.playEffect('res/audio/sfx_coin.mp3');
```

Preloading is especially important for sound effects that need to play immediately on game events (hits, jumps, pickups). Without preloading, the first playback may have a noticeable delay while the file loads. Music is less critical to preload since it usually starts during scene transitions when a brief delay is acceptable.

Use the various stop methods and `end()` for full cleanup:

```typescript
// Stop only background music
cc.audioEngine.stopMusic();           // keeps audio data in memory
cc.audioEngine.stopMusic(true);       // stops AND releases audio data

// Stop a specific effect
cc.audioEngine.stopEffect(audioId);

// Stop all effects at once
cc.audioEngine.stopAllEffects();

// Pause all effects (can resume later)
cc.audioEngine.pauseAllEffects();
cc.audioEngine.resumeAllEffects();

// Unload a specific effect from memory
cc.audioEngine.unloadEffect('res/audio/sfx_hit.mp3');

// Full cleanup: stop everything and release all resources
cc.audioEngine.end();
```

`stopMusic(true)` passes `releaseData = true` to free the music file from memory. `stopAllEffects()` stops every playing effect. `unloadEffect(url)` removes a specific effect from the cache. `end()` is the nuclear option — it stops all audio and releases everything. Use `end()` on game exit or when completely done with audio.

Use `setMusicVolume` and `setEffectsVolume` independently:

```typescript
// Set music volume (0.0 = silent, 1.0 = full)
cc.audioEngine.setMusicVolume(0.5);   // 50% music volume

// Set effects volume
cc.audioEngine.setEffectsVolume(0.8); // 80% effects volume

// Read current volumes
const musicVol: number = cc.audioEngine.getMusicVolume();
const sfxVol: number = cc.audioEngine.getEffectsVolume();

cc.log('Music: ' + musicVol + ', SFX: ' + sfxVol);
```

Both volume controls are global — `setMusicVolume` affects the single background music track, and `setEffectsVolume` affects ALL playing sound effects simultaneously. Volumes are clamped to 0.0–1.0 range. These settings persist until changed again or `end()` is called.

`playEffect` has multiple optional parameters beyond the URL:

```typescript
cc.audioEngine.playEffect(
    url: string,       // path to the sound file
    loop?: boolean,    // repeat? default false
    pitch?: number,    // playback speed/pitch
    pan?: number,      // stereo panning (-1 left, 0 center, 1 right)
    gain?: number      // volume multiplier for this effect
): number | null       // returns audio ID or null
```

**Examples:**
```typescript
// Simple one-shot
cc.audioEngine.playEffect('res/audio/sfx_coin.mp3');

// Looping ambient sound
const windId = cc.audioEngine.playEffect('res/audio/sfx_wind.mp3', true);

// High-pitched, panned right, lower volume
cc.audioEngine.playEffect('res/audio/sfx_hit.mp3', false, 1.5, 0.8, 0.6);

// Low-pitched, panned left
cc.audioEngine.playEffect('res/audio/sfx_explosion.mp3', false, 0.7, -0.8, 1.0);
```

The return value is a numeric audio ID for controlling this specific effect instance, or `null` if playback failed. The `pitch`, `pan`, and `gain` parameters are applied per-effect on top of the global effects volume.

```typescript
interface AudioConfig {
    musicVolume: number;
    sfxVolume: number;
    musicEnabled: boolean;
    sfxEnabled: boolean;
}

class AudioManager {
    private config: AudioConfig;
    private activeEffects: Map<string, number> = new Map();

    private static readonly DEFAULT_CONFIG: AudioConfig = {
        musicVolume: 0.7,
        sfxVolume: 0.8,
        musicEnabled: true,
        sfxEnabled: true
    };

    constructor(config?: Partial<AudioConfig>) {
        this.config = { ...AudioManager.DEFAULT_CONFIG, ...config };
        this.applyVolumes();
    }

    private applyVolumes(): void {
        cc.audioEngine.setMusicVolume(
            this.config.musicEnabled ? this.config.musicVolume : 0
        );
        cc.audioEngine.setEffectsVolume(
            this.config.sfxEnabled ? this.config.sfxVolume : 0
        );
    }

    preloadAll(musicPaths: string[], sfxPaths: string[]): void {
        for (const path of musicPaths) {
            cc.audioEngine.preloadMusic(path);
        }
        for (const path of sfxPaths) {
            cc.audioEngine.preloadEffect(path);
        }
    }

    playMusic(path: string, loop: boolean = true): void {
        if (!this.config.musicEnabled) return;
        cc.audioEngine.playMusic(path, loop);
    }

    stopMusic(release: boolean = false): void {
        cc.audioEngine.stopMusic(release);
    }

    playSfx(path: string, loop: boolean = false): number | null {
        if (!this.config.sfxEnabled) return null;
        const id = cc.audioEngine.playEffect(path, loop);
        if (id !== null && loop) {
            this.activeEffects.set(path, id);
        }
        return id;
    }

    stopSfx(path: string): void {
        const id = this.activeEffects.get(path);
        if (id !== undefined) {
            cc.audioEngine.stopEffect(id);
            this.activeEffects.delete(path);
        }
    }

    setMusicVolume(vol: number): void {
        this.config.musicVolume = vol;
        cc.audioEngine.setMusicVolume(vol);
    }

    setSfxVolume(vol: number): void {
        this.config.sfxVolume = vol;
        cc.audioEngine.setEffectsVolume(vol);
    }

    toggleMusic(enabled: boolean): void {
        this.config.musicEnabled = enabled;
        if (!enabled) {
            cc.audioEngine.pauseMusic();
        } else {
            cc.audioEngine.resumeMusic();
        }
        this.applyVolumes();
    }

    cleanup(): void {
        cc.audioEngine.stopAllEffects();
        cc.audioEngine.stopMusic();
        this.activeEffects.clear();
    }
}

// Usage:
const audio = new AudioManager({ musicVolume: 0.5 });
audio.preloadAll(
    ['res/audio/bgm_main.mp3'],
    ['res/audio/sfx_hit.mp3', 'res/audio/sfx_coin.mp3']
);
audio.playMusic('res/audio/bgm_main.mp3');
audio.playSfx('res/audio/sfx_coin.mp3');
```

This manager wraps `cc.audioEngine` with enable/disable toggles, volume tracking, looping effect management, and preloading. The `activeEffects` map tracks looping effects by path for later stopping.

```typescript
class MusicTransition {
    private targetMusic: string;
    private targetLoop: boolean;
    private fadeSteps: number = 20;
    private currentStep: number = 0;
    private originalVolume: number;
    private layer: cc.Layer;

    constructor(layer: cc.Layer) {
        this.layer = layer;
        this.originalVolume = cc.audioEngine.getMusicVolume();
    }

    crossfadeTo(newTrack: string, duration: number, loop: boolean = true): void {
        this.targetMusic = newTrack;
        this.targetLoop = loop;
        this.originalVolume = cc.audioEngine.getMusicVolume();
        this.currentStep = 0;

        cc.audioEngine.preloadMusic(newTrack);

        const interval = duration / (this.fadeSteps * 2);

        // Fade out current music
        const fadeOutCallback = () => {
            this.currentStep++;
            const vol = this.originalVolume * (1 - this.currentStep / this.fadeSteps);
            cc.audioEngine.setMusicVolume(Math.max(0, vol));

            if (this.currentStep >= this.fadeSteps) {
                this.layer.unschedule(fadeOutCallback);
                this.startFadeIn(interval);
            }
        };
        this.layer.schedule(fadeOutCallback, interval);
    }

    private startFadeIn(interval: number): void {
        cc.audioEngine.stopMusic();
        cc.audioEngine.playMusic(this.targetMusic, this.targetLoop);
        cc.audioEngine.setMusicVolume(0);
        this.currentStep = 0;

        const fadeInCallback = () => {
            this.currentStep++;
            const vol = this.originalVolume * (this.currentStep / this.fadeSteps);
            cc.audioEngine.setMusicVolume(Math.min(this.originalVolume, vol));

            if (this.currentStep >= this.fadeSteps) {
                this.layer.unschedule(fadeInCallback);
            }
        };
        this.layer.schedule(fadeInCallback, interval);
    }
}

// Usage:
class GameLayer extends cc.Layer {
    private musicTransition: MusicTransition;

    init(): boolean {
        this.musicTransition = new MusicTransition(this);
        cc.audioEngine.playMusic('res/audio/bgm_menu.mp3', true);
        return true;
    }

    onStartGame(): void {
        this.musicTransition.crossfadeTo('res/audio/bgm_battle.mp3', 2.0);
    }
}
```

Since `cc.audioEngine` only supports one music track at a time, this simulates crossfade by fading out the current track, switching, then fading in the new one. The `schedule` callback gradually adjusts `setMusicVolume` over multiple steps.

