```typescript
class AmbientSoundSystem {
    private sounds: Map<string, number> = new Map();
    private paths: Map<string, string> = new Map();

    addAmbientSound(name: string, path: string, volume: number): void {
        // Remove existing sound with same name
        this.removeAmbientSound(name);

        cc.audioEngine.preloadEffect(path);
        const id = cc.audioEngine.playEffect(path, true, 1.0, 0, volume);
        if (id !== null) {
            this.sounds.set(name, id);
            this.paths.set(name, path);
        }
    }

    removeAmbientSound(name: string): void {
        const id = this.sounds.get(name);
        if (id !== undefined) {
            cc.audioEngine.stopEffect(id);
            this.sounds.delete(name);
            this.paths.delete(name);
        }
    }

    removeAll(): void {
        for (const [name] of this.sounds) {
            this.removeAmbientSound(name);
        }
    }
}

// Usage:
const ambient = new AmbientSoundSystem();
ambient.addAmbientSound('wind', 'res/audio/amb_wind.mp3', 0.3);
ambient.addAmbientSound('rain', 'res/audio/amb_rain.mp3', 0.5);
ambient.addAmbientSound('birds', 'res/audio/amb_birds.mp3', 0.2);

// Remove specific sound
ambient.removeAmbientSound('rain');

// Clean up all
ambient.removeAll();
```

Each ambient sound is a looping effect with the `gain` parameter controlling its individual volume. Sounds are tracked by name for easy removal. `addAmbientSound` removes any existing sound with the same name first to prevent duplicates. `preloadEffect` ensures minimal latency.

instruction:
Find and fix the bug in this audio settings code:

```typescript
class AudioSettings {
    private musicVol: number = 0.7;
    private sfxVol: number = 0.8;

    setMusicVolume(vol: number): void {
        this.musicVol = vol;
    }

    setSfxVolume(vol: number): void {
        this.sfxVol = vol;
    }

    applySettings(): void {
        cc.audioEngine.setMusicVolume(this.musicVol);
        cc.audioEngine.setEffectsVolume(this.sfxVol);
    }
}

const settings = new AudioSettings();
settings.setMusicVolume(0.3);
// Music doesn't change volume!
```

output:
The bug is that `setMusicVolume` only stores the value locally but never calls `cc.audioEngine.setMusicVolume`. The user would need to also call `applySettings()`, which is easy to forget.

**Fixed code:**
```typescript
class AudioSettings {
    private musicVol: number = 0.7;
    private sfxVol: number = 0.8;

    setMusicVolume(vol: number): void {
        this.musicVol = Math.max(0, Math.min(1, vol));
        cc.audioEngine.setMusicVolume(this.musicVol);  // Apply immediately
    }

    setSfxVolume(vol: number): void {
        this.sfxVol = Math.max(0, Math.min(1, vol));
        cc.audioEngine.setEffectsVolume(this.sfxVol);  // Apply immediately
    }

    applySettings(): void {
        cc.audioEngine.setMusicVolume(this.musicVol);
        cc.audioEngine.setEffectsVolume(this.sfxVol);
    }
}

const settings = new AudioSettings();
settings.setMusicVolume(0.3);  // Now works immediately
```

The fix applies the volume to `cc.audioEngine` immediately when set, in addition to storing it. Also adds clamping to keep values in 0–1 range. `applySettings` is still useful for restoring saved settings on startup.

```typescript
class AnimatedCharacterWithAudio extends cc.Layer {
    private skel: sp.SkeletonAnimation;

    private static readonly EVENT_SFX: Record<string, string> = {
        'footstep': 'res/audio/sfx_step.mp3',
        'sword_swing': 'res/audio/sfx_swing.mp3',
        'hit_impact': 'res/audio/sfx_hit.mp3'
    };

    constructor() {
        super();
        this.init();
    }

    init(): boolean {
        this.preloadSounds();

        this.skel = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
        this.skel.setPosition(240, 160);
        this.addChild(this.skel);
        this.skel.setAnimation(0, 'run', true);

        this.skel.setAnimationListener(this, (
            track: spine.TrackEntry,
            type: number,
            event: spine.Event
        ) => {
            if (type === sp.AnimationEventType.EVENT) {
                this.onSpineEvent(event);
            }
        });

        return true;
    }

    private preloadSounds(): void {
        for (const key in AnimatedCharacterWithAudio.EVENT_SFX) {
            cc.audioEngine.preloadEffect(AnimatedCharacterWithAudio.EVENT_SFX[key]);
        }
    }

    private onSpineEvent(event: spine.Event): void {
        const sfxPath = AnimatedCharacterWithAudio.EVENT_SFX[event.data.name];
        if (sfxPath) {
            cc.audioEngine.playEffect(sfxPath);
        }
    }
}
```

The integration works by mapping Spine event names to audio file paths. When the Spine animation listener fires an `EVENT` type, it looks up the event name in the map and plays the corresponding sound effect. Sounds are preloaded at initialization for instant playback. This keeps animation and audio perfectly synchronized since Spine events fire at the exact frame defined in the Spine editor.

`willPlayMusic()` and `isMusicPlaying()` check different conditions:

**`isMusicPlaying(): boolean`**
- Returns `true` if music is actively playing right now
- Returns `false` if music is paused, stopped, or never started

**`willPlayMusic(): boolean`**
- Returns `true` if the music system is ready and able to play
- Checks if music is loaded and the audio engine is initialized

```typescript
// Music not started yet
cc.log(cc.audioEngine.isMusicPlaying());  // false
cc.log(cc.audioEngine.willPlayMusic());   // true (engine is ready)

// Start music
cc.audioEngine.playMusic('res/audio/bgm.mp3', true);
cc.log(cc.audioEngine.isMusicPlaying());  // true

// Pause
cc.audioEngine.pauseMusic();
cc.log(cc.audioEngine.isMusicPlaying());  // false (paused)
cc.log(cc.audioEngine.willPlayMusic());   // true (can resume)

// After end()
cc.audioEngine.end();
cc.log(cc.audioEngine.willPlayMusic());   // false (engine shut down)
```

Use `isMusicPlaying()` to check current playback state. Use `willPlayMusic()` to check if the audio system is operational before attempting to play.

`unloadEffect` removes a specific sound effect file from the audio engine's cache, freeing its memory:

```typescript
cc.audioEngine.unloadEffect(url: string): void
```

**Usage:**
```typescript
// Preload effects for current level
cc.audioEngine.preloadEffect('res/audio/sfx_laser.mp3');
cc.audioEngine.preloadEffect('res/audio/sfx_explosion.mp3');

// Use them during gameplay
cc.audioEngine.playEffect('res/audio/sfx_laser.mp3');
cc.audioEngine.playEffect('res/audio/sfx_explosion.mp3');

// Level complete — unload level-specific effects
cc.audioEngine.unloadEffect('res/audio/sfx_laser.mp3');
cc.audioEngine.unloadEffect('res/audio/sfx_explosion.mp3');
```

**When to use:**
- After leaving a level that has unique sound effects
- When memory is tight and certain effects won't be needed again
- During scene transitions to free resources from the previous scene

**When NOT to use:**
- For effects used across multiple scenes (UI clicks, common hits)
- While the effect is still playing — stop it first with `stopEffect`

For bulk cleanup, `end()` releases everything at once. `unloadEffect` is for selective, granular memory management.

```typescript
class VolumeController {
    private musicVolume: number;
    private sfxVolume: number;
    private isMuted: boolean = false;

    constructor() {
        this.musicVolume = cc.audioEngine.getMusicVolume();
        this.sfxVolume = cc.audioEngine.getEffectsVolume();
    }

    setMusicPercent(percent: number): void {
        this.musicVolume = Math.max(0, Math.min(1, percent / 100));
        if (!this.isMuted) {
            cc.audioEngine.setMusicVolume(this.musicVolume);
        }
    }

    setSfxPercent(percent: number): void {
        this.sfxVolume = Math.max(0, Math.min(1, percent / 100));
        if (!this.isMuted) {
            cc.audioEngine.setEffectsVolume(this.sfxVolume);
        }
    }

    getMusicPercent(): number {
        return Math.round(this.musicVolume * 100);
    }

    getSfxPercent(): number {
        return Math.round(this.sfxVolume * 100);
    }

    toggleMute(): boolean {
        this.isMuted = !this.isMuted;
        if (this.isMuted) {
            cc.audioEngine.setMusicVolume(0);
            cc.audioEngine.setEffectsVolume(0);
        } else {
            cc.audioEngine.setMusicVolume(this.musicVolume);
            cc.audioEngine.setEffectsVolume(this.sfxVolume);
        }
        return this.isMuted;
    }

    previewSfxVolume(): void {
        cc.audioEngine.playEffect('res/audio/sfx_click.mp3');
    }
}

// Usage:
const vol = new VolumeController();
vol.setMusicPercent(50);   // sets music to 0.5
vol.setSfxPercent(80);     // sets SFX to 0.8
vol.toggleMute();          // mutes all audio
vol.toggleMute();          // restores previous volumes
vol.previewSfxVolume();    // play a click to preview SFX level
```

This controller works with percentage values (0–100) for UI sliders, converting to the 0.0–1.0 range that `cc.audioEngine` uses. The mute toggle remembers previous volumes and restores them. `previewSfxVolume` lets users hear the current SFX level when adjusting the slider.

`rewindMusic()` restarts the currently playing background music from the beginning without stopping it first:

```typescript
// Start music
cc.audioEngine.playMusic('res/audio/bgm_main.mp3', true);

// After some time, restart from the beginning
cc.audioEngine.rewindMusic();
```

Unlike `stopMusic()` followed by `playMusic()`, `rewindMusic()` does not interrupt the audio engine's state — it simply resets the playback position to 0. Use it when:

- You want to manually restart a looping track from the beginning
- You want to replay a non-looping track without calling `playMusic` again
- A game event requires the music to restart (e.g., player retries a level)

Note that `rewindMusic` only works if music was previously started with `playMusic`. If music is paused, rewinding will reset the position but the music remains paused until `resumeMusic` is called.

```typescript
class Jukebox {
    private tracks: string[];
    private currentIndex: number = 0;
    private layer: cc.Layer;
    private isPlaying: boolean = false;

    private static readonly CHECK_INTERVAL = 0.5;

    constructor(layer: cc.Layer, tracks: string[]) {
        this.layer = layer;
        this.tracks = tracks;
        for (const track of tracks) {
            cc.audioEngine.preloadMusic(track);
        }
    }

    play(): void {
        if (this.tracks.length === 0) return;
        this.isPlaying = true;
        this.playCurrentTrack();
        this.layer.schedule(
            this.checkTrackEnd.bind(this),
            Jukebox.CHECK_INTERVAL
        );
    }

    stop(): void {
        this.isPlaying = false;
        cc.audioEngine.stopMusic();
        this.layer.unschedule(this.checkTrackEnd.bind(this));
    }

    skip(): void {
        this.advanceTrack();
        this.playCurrentTrack();
    }

    private playCurrentTrack(): void {
        const track = this.tracks[this.currentIndex];
        cc.audioEngine.playMusic(track, false);
    }

    private checkTrackEnd(): void {
        if (!this.isPlaying) return;
        if (!cc.audioEngine.isMusicPlaying()) {
            this.advanceTrack();
            this.playCurrentTrack();
        }
    }

    private advanceTrack(): void {
        this.currentIndex = (this.currentIndex + 1) % this.tracks.length;
    }
}

// Usage:
const jukebox = new Jukebox(this, [
    'res/audio/bgm_track1.mp3',
    'res/audio/bgm_track2.mp3',
    'res/audio/bgm_track3.mp3'
]);
jukebox.play();
jukebox.skip();
```

The jukebox preloads all tracks, plays each non-looping, and polls `isMusicPlaying()` every 0.5 seconds. When a track ends, it advances to the next one. `skip()` immediately moves to the next track. Since `cc.audioEngine` only supports one music track at a time, each `playMusic` call replaces the previous one.
